body:
Following example is a legit FLOP description. The case is "incomplete", meaning some values of STATE are not specified, but in the context of a sequential procedural block that means that the flop HOLDS the state for that case.

```verilog
module test(
    input logic clk,
    input logic [1:0] state,
    output logic [3:0] x
);
    localparam IDLE   = 2'd0;
    localparam ROTATE = 2'd1;
    localparam DONE   = 2'd2;

    always @(posedge clk) begin
        case (state)
            IDLE: x <= 1;
            ROTATE: x <= 2;
            DONE: x <= 3;
        endcase
    end
endmodule
```

This code is totally equivalent to adding a default branch in which we do `x <= x`, but it's redundant.

Running this code through verilator results in `CASEINCOMPLETE` warning:

```
verilator --trace --binary -Wno-TIMESCALEMOD -Wno-WIDTHTRUNC --top tb ../../rtl/cordic.v ../../tb/cordic_tb.v
%Warning-CASEINCOMPLETE: ../../rtl/cordic.v:11:9: Case values incompletely covered (example pattern 0x3)
   11 |         case (state)
      |         ^~~~
                         ... For warning description see https://verilator.org/warn/CASEINCOMPLETE?v=5.040
                         ... Use "/* verilator lint_off CASEINCOMPLETE */" and lint_on around source to disable this message.
%Error: Exiting due to 1 warning(s)
make: *** [Makefile:28: obj_dir/Vtb] Error 1
```
Is this a bug? In my opinion *yes*, since the incomplete case in the context of a procedural sequential block *is* a valid description (valid if for whatever reason we restrict ourselves to only describing valid synchronous logic in verilog, apart from that this is 100% valid LRM code), but I understand in the end it's a matter of conventions.

If we describe the same logic with `if` statements leaving unspecified the final `else` branch, which is the exact same logic as the case statement, we get no errors, which is inconsistent:

```verilog
module test(
    input logic clk,
    input logic [1:0] state,
    output logic [3:0] x
);
    localparam IDLE   = 2'd0;
    localparam ROTATE = 2'd1;
    localparam DONE   = 2'd2;

    always @(posedge clk) begin
        if (state == IDLE) x <= 1;
        else if (state == ROTATE) x <= 2;
        else if (state == DONE) x <= 3;
    end
endmodule
```

I'd be open to trying out a solution if there's an agreement that this is something that needs to be solved.

